## 26. Figure-Level vs Axes-Level Functions

## Axes-Level Functions

Examples:

```python
sns.scatterplot()
sns.lineplot()
sns.boxplot()
sns.histplot()
sns.heatmap()
```

They draw onto a Matplotlib axis.

Example:

```python
figure, axis = plt.subplots()

sns.scatterplot(
    data=students,
    x="study_hours",
    y="exam_score",
    ax=axis,
)
```

## Figure-Level Functions

Examples:

```python
sns.relplot()
sns.catplot()
sns.displot()
sns.pairplot()
```

They create and manage their own figure.

For example, `catplot()` is documented as a figure-level interface for categorical plots. ([seaborn.pydata.org][7])

```python
chart = sns.catplot(
    data=students,
    x="course",
    y="exam_score",
    kind="box",
)
```

Do not pass a normal Matplotlib `ax` argument to functions that create their own figure unless that function explicitly supports it.

---

## 27. Faceting

Faceting creates separate charts for different groups.

```python
sns.relplot(
    data=students,
    x="study_hours",
    y="exam_score",
    col="course",
    kind="scatter",
)

plt.show()
```

This creates one chart for each course.

```text
Python chart | AI chart | Data Science chart
```

Faceting is useful when putting every group on one chart becomes cluttered.

